[Claude]: Based on my thorough investigation, I have identified and confirmed one critical vulnerability in the requests library related to credential leakage during redirects. Let me complete my review:

## Summary of Findings

I've investigated all 12 functions identified in the CodeQL query results related to redirects and authentication:

1. **`_basic_auth_str`** - Basic auth string generation (not vulnerable)
2. **`handle_redirect`** - Digest auth redirect handling (not vulnerable)
3. **`add_unredirected_header`** - Cookie jar header handling (not vulnerable)
4. **`prepare_auth`** - Auth preparation (not vulnerable)
5. **`is_redirect`** - Redirect detection (not vulnerable)
6. **`is_permanent_redirect`** - Permanent redirect detection (not vulnerable)
7. **`get_redirect_target`** - Redirect URL extraction (not vulnerable)
8. **`resolve_redirects`** - Main redirect resolution loop (calls rebuild_auth)
9. **`rebuild_auth`** - **VULNERABLE** - Missing scheme validation
10. **`get_netrc_auth`** - Netrc auth retrieval (not vulnerable)
11. **`get_auth_from_url`** - URL auth extraction (not vulnerable)
12. **`urldefragauth`** - URL defragmentation (not vulnerable)

The critical vulnerability is in the `rebuild_auth` function which only checks hostname changes but not scheme changes, allowing Authorization headers to leak when redirecting from HTTPS to HTTP on the same hostname.

